# Summary

The Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE) entry describes the vulnerability of not properly validating inputs used for loop conditions, which can result in denial of service due to excessive resource consumption from endless looping. This is caused by failing to set a proper exit condition for the loop based on the length or other properties of the input. 

The consequence is primarily availability impact in the form of denial of service from CPU resource exhaustion. It is relevant to secure coding practices for software development. Potential mitigations include not using user-controlled data for loop conditions, and performing input validation on data before using it to control loop iteration.

Automated static analysis tools can detect instances of this weakness in code by modeling data flow and control flow to find vulnerabilities.

# Summary bullet points

* Failing to validate loop condition input can let attacker-controlled data determine loop iterations
* Leads to denial of service through endless looping consuming CPU resources
* Mitigate by not basing loops on user input or validating input first
* Causes availability impact from resource exhaustion
* Static analysis can automatically detect flaws by modeling data and control flow
* Relevant to secure coding standards and practices

